Phase 6 Part 7 - PWA verification
(run against the ACTUAL frontend/public/sw.js and
frontend/public/manifest.webmanifest files)

manifest.webmanifest:
- VALID JSON
- PASS: has name, short_name, start_url, display=standalone
- PASS: has a 192x192 icon
- PASS: has a 512x512 icon
- PASS: has a maskable-purpose icon
(the above are Chrome's actual PWA installability criteria for the
manifest half of the check -- the other half, a fetch-handling service
worker, is verified below)

sw.js (run against a fake ServiceWorkerGlobalScope + Cache API + fetch,
simulating install/activate/fetch events -- routing logic under test is
the real, unmodified file):
1. PASS - install event precaches the known app-shell URLs
2. PASS - activate event deletes old-versioned caches
3. PASS - activate event keeps the current-versioned cache
4. PASS - fetch to a same-origin /api/ path is never intercepted (always network)
5. PASS - fetch to a cross-origin URL is never intercepted (always network)
6. PASS - a non-GET (POST/etc) fetch is never intercepted
7. PASS - a navigation request falls back to the cached app shell when the network fails
8. PASS - an uncached static asset request goes to the network
9. PASS - that static asset's response gets written into the runtime cache

9/9 checks passed. This confirms the service worker never touches
mutating requests or API calls (the actively-harmful case for a rentals/
payments app) while still providing a working offline app-shell fallback.

Node.js has no real ServiceWorkerGlobalScope, so this cannot be a
substitute for testing in an actual browser (Chrome DevTools ->
Application -> Service Workers, and Lighthouse's PWA audit) before
relying on this for a real launch -- noted in
docs/phase-6-part7-mobile.md.
